R and RStudio

Throughout this module we will work with the statistical programming language R (https://www.r-project.org/). Although it is possible to type commands directly into the R console, we will work with R through the integrated development environment RStudio (https://rstudio.com/). Please install R and then RStudio on your computer before the first practical.

Figure 1: A screenshot of the RStudio program, showing the console and an R script.

You are encouraged to complete the practical work in an R script, so that you can save it to view later or to work on in future practicals. This will also be important in the coursework, since you are encouraged to include the code from your R script in an appendix.

Working with a script

We want to be able to save any code that we write. In the top left corner, click File then New file and then R script. This will open a new R script where you can write reusable code.

We also want to load a data set. Download the file galaxies.Rdata from Minerva and save it in a folder on your computer. For example, on my computer, I put this data is in a folder whose location is C:\Users\benja\Desktop\R prac, so I set this as my working directory:

setwd("C:/Users/benjamin/Desktop/R prac")

When you have saved the data set in a folder on your own computer, set that folder as your working directory using the setwd() function as above. Click Run at the top of the script window to run this code. Note that the forward slash in the folder location has to be changed to a backward slash in R. Also, don’t forget the quotation marks.

We can save this code by clicking Save current document at the top of the script.

Exploring a data set

To load the galaxies data, we type and run

load(file = "galaxies.Rdata")     # Don't forget the quotation marks.

We will work with this data set many times in this module, so it is important for us to become familiar with it. To show the first \(10\) rows of the data set, type

galaxies[1:10, ]

Each row contains data for a single galaxy. Typing nrow(galaxies) tells us the number of rows. Typing names(galaxies) tells us the names of the variables (columns) on which we have data. Typing dim(galaxies) gives us the numbers of rows and columns (respectively).

Figure 2: An artist’s impression of the Milky Way and its globular clusters. Credit: ESA/Hubble, NASA, L Calcada, M Kormesser. https://www.spacetelescope.org/videos/heic1905b


Figure 3: An image of the elliptical Fornax galaxy, with four of its globular clusters circled. Credit: ESO/Digitized Sky Survey 2. https://www.spacetelescope.org/images/heic1425g

Our variables are:

  • Galaxy, the identifier/name of the galaxy.
  • GlobularClusters, the number of globular star clusters orbiting the the core of the galaxy.
  • BlackHoleMass, the mass of the black hole at the centre of the galaxy, on a logarithmic scale. A mass of \(6\) means \(10^6\) times the mass of our Sun.
  • Distance, the distance from Earth in light-years. A distance of \(10^9\) means light from the galaxy would take a billion years to reach us.
  • Vdispersion, the velocity dispersion: how fast (in km/second) objects in the galaxy are moving relative to each other.
  • Eradius, the effective radius: the radius (in light-years) at which half of the total light of the galaxy is emitted.
  • Type, the visual appearance: Elliptical, Spiral or Lenticular.

To select the second variable, number of globular clusters, there are three options:

galaxies[ , 2]

galaxies$GlobularClusters

galaxies[ , "GlobularClusters"]

To view these in order, from smallest to largest, we use the sort() function:

sort(galaxies$GlobularClusters)

Now we check which galaxies have over \(10000\) globular clusters by making a vector of TRUE or FALSE values:

galaxies$GlobularClusters > 10000

We can count the number of such galaxies:

sum(galaxies$GlobularClusters > 10000)

We can even identify specific observation numbers:

which(galaxies$GlobularClusters > 10000)

To show only the galaxies with at least \(10000\) globular clusters, we set a condition on the rows:

galaxies[galaxies$GlobularClusters > 10000, ]

To show only the name and type of these galaxies:

galaxies[galaxies$GlobularClusters > 10000, c("Galaxy", "Type")]

To extract seventh variable of the first galaxy:

galaxies[1, 7]

This is the visual type of the Milky Way galaxy, therefore we could have instead (using the equality operator, ==) typed

galaxies[galaxies$Galaxy == "MilkyWay", "Type"]

since galaxies$Galaxy == "MilkyWay" identifies which of the galaxies in our data set are called "MilkyWay".

Manipulating a data set

The variable BlackHoleMass is the mass of the black hole at the centre of each galaxy, measured on a logarithmic scale. We can easily calculate every black hole mass in units of solar masses, instead of on the logarithmic scale:

10^(galaxies$BlackHoleMass)

Store this vector in a variable called y:

y <- 10^(galaxies$BlackHoleMass)

Run the code

galaxies$BHM2 <- y

and then view the first \(3\) lines of the galaxies. What do you see?

Exercise 5 (distance from Earth) The variable Distance gives the distance from each galaxy to Earth, in light-years. What code would we write to convert this distance to miles and then include it as a column in our data set?

It is also easy to remove rows and columns from a data set. For example,

nonspiral <- galaxies[galaxies$Type != "Spiral", ]

will create a data set nonspiral containing only rows for galaxies that are not spiral galaxies (since != means “not equal to”).

manyclusters <- galaxies[galaxies$GlobularClusters >= 1000, ]

excludes all rows for galaxies with fewer than a thousand globular clusters (since >= means “greater than or equal to”).

galaxies2 <- galaxies[ , -c(1, 3)]

doesn’t remove any galaxies from our data set, but it does remove columns \(1\) and \(3\).

We can see the impact on the amount of data by applying the dim() function:

dim(galaxies)
dim(nonspiral)
dim(manyclusters)
dim(galaxies2)

If a column contains missing values, recorded as NA, it is often helpful to remove rows with missing values by using the is.na() function. For example,

galaxies <- galaxies[!is.na(galaxies$Distance) , ]

will remove any rows for galaxies with no distance to Earth recorded. Has this changed our data set here? Try typing is.na(galaxies$Distance) and !is.na(galaxies$Distance) to explain. What do you think ! does? Try typing help("!").

Loops

We often need to perform a task many times. For, example we might need to calculate an average for multiple columns of a very large data set. To avoid the need to write a line of code for each column, we could use a for loop that iterates over each column in the data set. We can illustrate this using our galaxies data:

for(i in 2:6){
  print(sum(galaxies[ , i])/nrow(galaxies))  
}

This code will print the averages of columns \(2\), \(3\), \(4\), \(5\) and \(6\). In this loop, for(i in 2:6) says that everything inside the curly brackets { } will be run for i = 2, i = 3, …, i = 6. Thus the calculation sum(galaxies[ , i])/nrow(galaxies) is performed for each index i, and the result will be printed thanks to the print() function.

We can also add if statements, to our loops. For example:

for(i in 2:6){
  
  if(sum(galaxies[ , i])/nrow(galaxies) < 1000){
    
    print(sum(galaxies[ , i])/nrow(galaxies))  
  }
}

Now the average of the \(i\)-th column will only be printed if it is less than \(1000\). The condition inside if() can be any statement that produces a value of TRUE or FALSE, and the commands inside the subsequent curly brackets will only be performed by R if the statement is true.

Unlike some other programming languages, indentation is not necessary for loops in R. However, it is encouraged to make your code easier to follow.

Exercise 6 (loops) Run the following loop in R, then try to explain in plain English what this loop does. 
for(i in 1:nrow(galaxies)){
    
     if(galaxies$BlackHoleMass[i] > 9){
    
          print(galaxies[i, "Distance"]/1000)
        
     }
}

Using what we have learned in previous sections, how might this be achieved in a single line of code?

Learning more about R

There are many free online resources available for learning R, for any level of ability in statistics or programming. I have included here some that I have found to be helpful in the past. For example, university lecturers often make their teaching materials available to the public. Particularly useful here are some introductory notes on R from Oxford and Cambridge:

  • Evans R. R Programming. https://www.stats.ox.ac.uk/~evans/Rprog/
  • Altham P. Introduction to Statistical Modelling in R. http://www.statslab.cam.ac.uk/~pat/redwsheets.pdf

Students with a fairly advanced understanding of linear regression might find the notes of Julian Faraway more helpful. These notes assume a greater level of mathematical ability, but they also offer much deeper insight into the analyses.

  • Faraway J. Practical Regression and ANOVA using R. https://julianfaraway.github.io/faraway/PRA/

Anyone who who feels comfortable with the statistics and wants to focus entirely on learning R might prefer to read the early chapters of book of Norman Matloff. This book gives a particularly thorough introduction to the various data structures in R and how they are manipulated.

  • Matloff N. The Art of R Programming. http://heather.cs.ucdavis.edu/~matloff/132/NSPpart.pdf

Solutions

Solution to Exercise 1

4 * 2       # Multiplies the two numbers.

sin(pi)     # Evaluates the function sin at 
            # the number pi. Note that this 
            # is not equal to 0 as we might 
            # expect, because R can only provide
            # approximate values of this function.

?sin        # Takes us to the help page, which 
            # explains the function. Using ?, we 
            # can find information on any R function.

?pi         # We can also apply ? to understand 
            # built-in constants.
a = 2       # Store the number 2 in an object called a.

a           # Returns the number stored in a.

A           # Returns nothing because R is case 
            # sensitive and we only created an 
            # object called a, not A.

# a = 5     # This does nothing because anything
            # following "#" on a line of code 
            # will be treated as a comment by R, 
            # not as part of the code. We often 
            # use comments to describe and explain
            # sections of our code.

a           # Returns 2 because a = 5 did not run.
b <- 3      # Stores 3 in b. Equivalent to b = 3.

b           # Returns 3, as expected.

4 -> b      # Stores 4 in an object b. This is 
            # equivalent to b = 4 but NOT 
            # equivalent to 4 = b, since 
            # = is not symmetrical.

sqrt(b)     # Square root of b. See ?sqrt.

b^2         # Square of b. See ?"^". 

b == 4      # Checks equality: whether b is 
            # equal to 4. Returns the logical
            # value TRUE if so, FALSE if not. 
            # It does not assign a value to b.

b == 2      # Checks equality again, this 
            # time returning FALSE.

Solution to Exercise 2

c(1, 3, 2)        # Returns the vector (1, 2, 3). 

3 + c(1, 3, 2)    # Addition is vectorised, since 
                  # 3 is added to each element of 
                  # the vector. Multiplication, 
                  # subtraction and division 
                  # behave similarly.

c(2, 3, 1) * c(5, 10, 20)   # A further example of how
                            # vectors behave. Multiplying 
                            # two vectors of equal length 
                            # leads to corresponding components 
                            # being multiplied. Addition, 
                            # subtraction and division are similar.

1:9        # Returns a vector of numbers 1 to 9.

30:10      # Returns a vector of numbers 30 to 10.
v <- c(1, 3, 2)   # Stores (1, 3, 2) in v. 

v                 # Returns v.

v == c(1, 3, 4)   # Checks if the elements 
                  # of v are equal to 1, 2, 
                  # 3 and 4 in that order. 

v[2]              # For any positive integer 
                  # i, v[i] will return 
                  # the i-th element of v.

v[c(2, 1)]        # Returns the second and 
                  # first elements of v 
                  # in the specified order. 

v[2:3]            # Returns the second and
                  # third elements.

v[2] <- 4         # Replaces the 4th element 
                  # of v with 4.

v                 # Returns (1, 4, 2).
w <- 4*c(0, 1, 4)    # Creates a vector w 
                     # containing 0, 4, 16.

sqrt(w)       # Takes the square root 
              # of each component. The 
              # sqrt() function is vectorised.

sum(w)        # Takes the sum of the numbers in w.

w <- 4        # Replaces the vector in w with 
              # the number 4. 

w             # Returns 4, as expected.

Solution to Exercise 6

for(i in 1:nrow(galaxies)){  # Iterates over each row number.
    
  # Require black hole mass of i-th galaxy to be > 9:
  
  if(galaxies$BlackHoleMass[i] > 9){ 
    
    # Divide the distance to the i-th galaxy by 1000 and print:
    
    print(galaxies[i, "Distance"]/1000)   
  }
}

For each row (galaxy) of our data, it checks if the black hole mass in greater than \(9\). If so, it prints the distance to the galaxy in units of thousands of light years. In other words, it tells us how far we are from any galaxies with particularly huge central black holes.

How might this be achieved in a single line of code?

galaxies[galaxies$BlackHoleMass > 9, "Distance"]/1000
